---
import MainLayout from '../../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
---

<MainLayout title="OOP in Go: Pragmatic Design">
    <div class="py-12">
        <article class="max-w-3xl">
            <h1 class="text-5xl font-bold gradient-text mb-4">OOP in Go: Pragmatic Design</h1>
            <div class="text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 mb-2">Published on June 10, 2026</div>
            <div class="flex gap-2 mb-8 flex-wrap">
                <span class="bg-purple-100 dark:bg-purple-900/30 text-purple-700 dark:text-purple-300 text-xs px-2 py-1 rounded">Go</span>
                <span class="bg-purple-100 dark:bg-purple-900/30 text-purple-700 dark:text-purple-300 text-xs px-2 py-1 rounded">OOP</span>
            </div>

            <section class="space-y-6">
                <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold">Go's Approach to OOP</h2>
                <p>Go doesn't have classes, but it has composition, interfaces, and methods. This article explores how to apply OOP principles pragmatically in Go.</p>
                
                <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold">Composition Over Inheritance</h2>
                <p>Go emphasizes composition through embedding, which provides flexibility without the complexity of inheritance hierarchies.</p>

                <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold">Interfaces for Abstraction</h2>
                <p>Go's implicit interfaces allow you to define contracts without explicit coupling. This leads to more flexible and testable code.</p>

                <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold">Conclusion</h2>
                <p>By embracing Go's philosophy of simplicity and composition, you can write clean, maintainable object-oriented code.</p>
            </section>

            <a href="/blog" class="inline-block mt-12 text-indigo-600 hover:text-indigo-700 font-medium">← Back to Blog</a>
        </article>
    </div>
</MainLayout>
